## Pull Request Conventions

### PR Scope

A PR **may span both `apps/api` and `apps/web`** when the changes are coupled (e.g. new endpoint + new page). This is preferred over separate PRs that must be merged in a specific order and create a brief period of inconsistency.

If a PR is backend-only (e.g. a migration or performance fix), that is fine too. Just note in the description that no frontend changes are needed.

### PR Title

Use [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/) format:

```
feat(users): add profile photo upload endpoint and UI
fix(auth): handle expired refresh token without redirect loop
chore(deps): upgrade API Platform to 3.3
docs(api-contract): document pagination envelope
migration(orders): add status_history column
```

Scope is optional but recommended. Use the feature domain (e.g. `auth`, `users`, `billing`), not the app name (`api`, `web`).

### PR Description Template

```markdown
## What
Brief summary of the change.

## Why
Ticket link or motivation.

## How
Non-obvious implementation notes. Include a diagram if helpful.

## API Changes
- [ ] No API changes
- [ ] New endpoint: `METHOD /path` (see api-contract.md)
- [ ] Changed response shape: describe old vs new

## Shared Types
- [ ] No type changes
- [ ] Updated: list changed interfaces

## Testing
How was this verified? (unit tests, manual test steps, screenshot)

## Checklist
- [ ] Lint passes
- [ ] Tests pass
- [ ] No secrets committed
- [ ] Docs updated (if needed)
```

### Review Expectations

- Review within 1 business day
- Block on correctness and security; suggest (not block) on style
- If a PR touches both apps, review the API contract coherence, not just individual files
- Leave a "Reviewed API contract" comment if you have verified the types match

